<BaseLayout
  title="How We Select Products and Guide Topics"
  seoTitle="How We Select Products and Guide Topics"
  description="How Australian Home Collective develops practical buying guidance, compares product types and controls future commercial recommendations."
>
  <header class="page-intro">
    <div class="narrow">
      <p class="eyebrow">Our recommendation methodology</p>
      <h1>How We Select Products and Guide Topics</h1>
      <p class="lead">
        A recommendation begins with a household decision, not a product we want to feature.
      </p>
    </div>
  </header>

  <section class="content narrow">
    <h2>How we develop recommendations</h2>
    <p>
      Our recommendations are based on practical suitability rather than product popularity,
      marketing claims, sales rankings or commission rates.
    </p>
    <p>Instead of asking only which product is best, we ask:</p>
    <ul class="feature-list">
      <li>Will it suit the reader's home and intended use?</li>
      <li>Will it fit the available space and delivery route?</li>
      <li>What is required to install and use it properly?</li>
      <li>What trade-offs should the buyer understand?</li>
      <li>What may matter during ownership and after-sales support?</li>
      <li>What commonly overlooked problems can be avoided?</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Our goal is to give readers a useful framework for their own circumstances.</p>

    <h2>Planning comes first</h2>
    <p>
      Every guide begins with the decision and the setting in which a product will be used.
      We encourage readers to understand the available space, access, installation requirements,
      compatibility, maintenance, future needs and practical constraints before considering a
      particular product.
    </p>
    <p>A well-planned purchase is more valuable than an impulse purchase.</p>

    <h2>What we may consider</h2>
    <p>The factors below are used when relevant. Not every factor applies to every category.</p>

    <h3>Practical suitability</h3>
    <p>Does the option suit the intended room, household, layout and purpose?</p>

    <h3>Dimensions and fit</h3>
    <p>
      Will the product fit the installation space? Have operating clearances, delivery access,
      packaged dimensions and full door or drawer movement been considered?
    </p>

    <h3>Compatibility</h3>
    <p>
      Will it work with existing furniture, appliances, services, fittings, systems and room
      layouts?
    </p>

    <h3>Installation requirements</h3>
    <p>
      Does the product require ventilation, plumbing, electrical work, structural fixing,
      specialised access or professional installation?
    </p>

    <h3>Usability</h3>
    <p>
      Can the product be opened, adjusted, loaded, cleaned and used as intended in the proposed
      position?
    </p>

    <h3>Long-term ownership</h3>
    <p>
      What should readers consider about running costs, maintenance access, durability
      indicators, consumables, repairability, replacement costs and future household needs?
    </p>

    <h3>After-sales support</h3>
    <p>
      What should readers investigate about written warranty terms, local service coverage,
      support channels, spare-parts availability and the party responsible for support? We
      teach readers what to check rather than making broad, unsupported claims about a brand's
      service.
    </p>

    <h3>Safety and authoritative requirements</h3>
    <p>
      Where relevant, we highlight manufacturer instructions, recognised Australian guidance
      and situations in which a qualified professional should be consulted.
    </p>

    <h2>Evidence and sources</h2>
    <p>We may use:</p>
    <ul class="feature-list">
      <li>Australian government and regulator information</li>
      <li>recognised safety or efficiency guidance</li>
      <li>manufacturer category guidance, manuals and installation instructions where they verify a practical constraint</li>
      <li>clearly described first-hand observations only when we have actually made them</li>
      <li>practical planning principles</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      We prefer primary sources and qualify information that varies or cannot be fully verified.
      Retailer product pages, bestseller lists, stock status and customer review counts are not
      treated as independent editorial evidence.
    </p>

    <h2>What we do not do</h2>
    <p>
      Australian Home Collective is not a product-testing laboratory unless a specific article
      clearly describes the testing conducted. We do not:
    </p>
    <ul class="feature-list">
      <li>claim to have tested, owned or inspected products when we have not</li>
      <li>rank products solely by commission, popularity or advertising relationships</li>
      <li>declare a product suitable without considering context</li>
      <li>treat marketing claims as independent evidence</li>
      <li>use retailer availability or review counts as proof of product quality</li>
      <li>publish current product or model recommendations before the commercial approval process is complete</li>
      <li>reduce a complex decision to an unexplained numerical score</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>How recommendations are expressed</h2>
    <p>
      Different homes, budgets and priorities often produce different reasonable choices. Our
      current guides compare product types and buying criteria rather than publishing named model
      shortlists. A named product recommendation may appear only after a formally approved
      commercial workflow has recorded the evidence, verification date and required disclosure.
    </p>

    <h2>Ratings and scores</h2>
    <p>
      Australian Home Collective does not assign arbitrary scores or Editor's Choice labels.
      If a structured score or comparison system is introduced in future, its criteria,
      weighting, evidence and limitations will be published clearly.
    </p>

    <h2>Commercial relationships</h2>
    <p>
      Affiliate or commercial relationships do not determine our methodology or conclusions.
      A commercial link can appear only after formal approval and must carry the required
      disclosure. The surrounding guidance must remain useful when a reader does not use the link.
      Read our{" "}
      <a href="/affiliate-disclosure/">Affiliate Disclosure</a>.
    </p>

    <h2>Interactive planning tools</h2>
    <p>
      Our tools help readers identify potential considerations and measurement conflicts. They
      do not provide engineering, installation, safety or delivery approval. Each tool should
      explain what it assesses, which information it needs, the assumptions it makes, what it
      cannot determine and when further verification is recommended.
    </p>

    <h2>Consumer rights information</h2>
    <p>
      Where ownership and warranty considerations are relevant, we may direct readers to
      authoritative information about Australian Consumer Law. We do not provide legal advice
      or decide how the law applies to an individual situation. See the ACCC's{" "}
      <ExternalLink href="https://www.accc.gov.au/consumers/buying-products-and-services/consumer-rights-and-guarantees">
        consumer rights and guarantees guidance
      </ExternalLink>.
    </p>

    <h2>Continuous improvement</h2>
    <p>
      We review and update content when guidance, standards, reader needs or our own practical
      understanding change. Substantive improvements may update the editorial review date.
    </p>
    <p><strong>Our guiding question is simple: will this help someone make a better decision for their home?</strong></p>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
